result.execSummary:
This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

[MK] case called at 1:41pm 
Defendant Kayli G. Schaller appears via videoconferencing from the Jefferson County Jail, in custody, along with Public Defender Jeffrey De La Rosa (the PD will appoint counsel).  Public Service Special Prosecutor Melanie Flint appears for the State of Wisconsin. 
The Court finds that the video-connection is sight and sound sufficient. 

The Defendant verifies that the date of birth listed on the Criminal Complaint is correct. Attorney De La Rosa provides an updated address in Tomah WI.
Service of Complaint admitted, reading waived, the charge and maximum penalties are recited.
Plea of "Not Guilty" is entered; speedy trial is waived by both parties.
The Court finds probable cause exists in the Criminal Complaint.  

The Court requires a $500 Signature Bond with conditions:
--no contact with Victim 1
--no possession or use of any financial transaction cards in another person's name
recess 1:46pm.
